<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Yeah, getting hit by a solar sail is a real bear! <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
And if you could use solar sails for interstellar travel, that would mean something.  A laser sail, OTOH, while in and of itself isn't dangerous, has a power source that can vaporize cities within the confines of their solar system (and maybe even do some damage to a planet in a neighboring star system depending on beam dispersion).  I believe the estimated amount of power is <!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://ffden-2.phys.uaf.edu/213.web.stuff/Scott%20Kircher/lightsails.html">43,000 terawatts</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--> or over 10 megatons worth of energy every second.  As I said interstellar propulsion=potential weapon.<br>
<br>
